    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Where drug discovery is considered, AI is deemed to have a game-changing potential. It is being used to classify candidate compounds in terms of their activity and other properties. AI is also used to discover informative biomarkers that correlate with tested outcomes. The advantage of using<br></br>AI is that they can be used to develop a predictive model even when our understanding of the underlying processes is limited. AI is used for structural bioinformatics by finding representations capable of capturing the<br></br>underlying principles and correlations are crucial for the success of applications of any AI technique. It is being used in target validation for discovering benchmark compounds set design, to predict the targetâ€™s role in disease, design of in silico compound libraries, to identify novel targets, to predict druggability of targets and to predict signaling systems. It is used in hit/lead identification for prediction of structure-activity relationships and ADMET properties. AI is applied in preclinical development for drug repurposing, selection of candidate patient population in clinical trials to increase success rates and pharmacovigilance. These applications are broadly classified and these can be further divided in subsections like reaction prediction in which the task is to infer how a set of molecules (starting materials) will react and what the product will be and in retrosynthesis, the aim is to propose how to make a target molecule, by deducing reactions in which the target molecule is the product and retrosynthesis, in which a search tree is built by working backward, analyzing molecules recursively and transforming them into simpler precursors until a known set of commercially<br></br>available building block molecules are obtained. There are also virtual screening methods which can be classified into two, ligand-based virtual screening which involves the similarity and the physicochemical analysis of active ligands to predict the activity of other compounds with similar<br></br>Characteristics and structure-based virtual screening which is used when the (3D) structure of the target receptor was already elucidated somehow.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="image3 cid-tt612oXwA9" id="image3-5" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
